<paragraph id="8BB736C8FFF0FFF36194FD9A0123F5F6" blockId="12.[151,1437,618,753]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D4BFFF0FFF36053FD9B0658F583" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[336,519,618,644]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculptissimus">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFF0FFF36053FD9B0658F583" box="[336,519,618,644]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. sculptissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group are recognized by the combination of the following characteristics: 1) small size, ca. 
<quantity id="4CF09B2DFFF0FFF36057FD7E05A6F5AE" box="[340,505,654,681]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.45" metricValueMin="2.25" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="2.35" valueMax="2.45" valueMin="2.25">2.25–2.45 mm</quantity>
; 2) black dorsal color; 3) elytral with costate or raised interseries; 4) pronotum deeply sculptured; 5) male genitalia lacking parameres, and lacking distal piece. Currently, three species are recognized: 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D4BFFF0FFF36194FD270560F5F7" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,319,726,752]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ampliarmus">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFF0FFF36194FD270560F5F7" box="[151,319,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. ampliarmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D4BFFF0FFF3604EFD270583F5F7" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[333,476,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="casuarius">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFF0FFF3604EFD270583F5F7" box="[333,476,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. casuarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D4BFFF0FFF36319FD27068EF5F7" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2021" box="[538,721,726,752]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculptissimus">
<emphasis id="B97CEADAFFF0FFF36319FD27068EF5F7" box="[538,721,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">H. sculptissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All three species are known only from 
<collectingCountry id="F31F7658FFF0FFF36591FD260089F5F7" box="[1170,1238,726,752]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13332A4DFFF0FFF365E5FD26011CF5F6" box="[1254,1347,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–56" captionStartId="80.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-28@80.[165,1422,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="80" captionText="FIGURES 55–56. Geographical distributions. 55. Endemics and near endemics. 56. H. bicarinatus and H. merkli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043352" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043352/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Figs. 55</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13332A4DFFF0FFF3644CFD260130F5F6" box="[1359,1391,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–58" captionStartId="81.[151,264,1928,1952]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1905]" captionTargetId="figure-15@81.[151,1435,181,1905]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="FIGURES 57–58. Geographical distributions. 57. Endemics and near endemics. 58. H. bituberculatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043356" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043356/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
